probably win this debate where interstellar spacecraft are conerned. Nuclear electric ion and plasma drive spacecraft<br>
will probably win this debate where interplanetary propulsion<br>
is concerned. Nuclear electric drives can be powered by <br>
 nuclear fission,nuclear fusion, or by matter=antimatter annhilation reactors, or even by beamed power as in a laser<br>
electric rocket  or ramjet..Also however when enough antimatter is availible for use as rocket/reactor fuel: then all of these things will ultimately be superceded  by spacecraft that  use propulsion systems which  are powered by the annhilation of matter and antimatter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/15/02 3:00:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear proplusion and politics.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Deadalas will probably win this debate where<br>
interstellar spacecraft are conerned.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 More likely beamed power for interstellar travel (unmanned micro probes, for a long time) will win out, because it works for small unmanned purposes, while there are still far too many things in the way of a manned interstellar mission. Smaller probes are being made all the time, and they are every bit as useful as bigger robotic probes.<br>
 Daedalus barely gets .2C, while Starwisp easily beats that, with <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>far</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> less investment.<br>
<br>
We probably don't even know the basics of what may be used eventually for manned interstellar trips -it's too far out, too difficult. The only thing we can see now is the expansion of space colonies out into &amp; past the cometary halo, and that's millennia per trip, and more of a lifestyle than a mission.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Nuclear electric ion and plasma drive spacecraft<br>
will probably win this debate where interplanetary<br>
propulsion is concerned.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 NEP is far, far too slow. We'd prefer to get crews to their destination before they've died from complications from long-duration space exposure.<br>
 Before we get the innovations to make VASIMR work, we'll use some of the same things (superconductors) in magnetic sails.<br>
 Even that is far out, because a far simpler alternative exists (with better performance), and it only takes some political will to use it: Orion (When we get the supercondutors, we'll use Mag-Orion).<br>
 The only reason why Orion seems unacceptable, is our limited viewpoint today: Nothing going on in space to get favorable public interest in reasonable proposals. The present political climate won't last forever -not past the first manned Mars landing, or private large-sale venture. Certainly not past the Chinese Lunar mission!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt;... when enough antimatter is availible for use as<br>
rocket/reactor fuel: then all of these things will<br>
ultimately be superceded by spacecraft that use<br>
propulsion systems which are powered by the<br>
annhilation of matter and antimatter.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The problem with matter-antimatter annihilation is the amounts of antimater needed. ACMF gets around this by using tiny amounts of antiprotons -which we can produce today, and almost store for the duration of the mission today.<br>
 Far more near-term is the anti-matter version of Daedalus: ACMF or the Penn St. ICAN design.<br>
<br>
 A discussion of various inertial confinement fusion (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.islandone.org/APC/Nuclear/11.html">ICF</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->) from the Island One Society and JPL.<br>
If ICF can be worked out (in any of the various forms, including possibly ACMF), I'll agree wholeheartedly that they'll replace all other interplanetary concepts (Far more efficient use of fissionables than Orion, for basically the same performance) <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8>Media and Politics</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.9.5.3<br>Copyright ©1999-2002 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

